"{\"uid\": \"express.co.uk-news-world-1902789-volocity-paris-olympics-flying-taxis\", \"text\": \"  Incredible flying taxis could ferry people to the Olympics for \\u00a3250 each.  German company Volocopter manufactures the \\\"VoloCity\\\", an electric aircraft aiming to be used at the Paris Olympics this summer.  The VoloCity is a two-seater aircraft (including the pilot's seat) equipped with batteries powering 18 rotors arranged in a ring above the cockpit.  To carry paying passengers, the VoloCity will have to obtain certification from the European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA).  Promotors are hoping to try them out during the Olympic and Paralympic Games, but aiming for certification by the European authorities in the autumn.  READ MORE:Eurostar tipped for huge new multi-million plan to add more routes    The VoloCity has been described by Volocopter as a \\\"game changer\\\" that will transport people between transport hubs \\\"whisper-quiet and emission-free\\\" for \\\"seamless, faster, and more convenient options\\\".  The Paris airports operator, ADP Group, has joined forces with the \\u00cele-de-France region and Volocopter to demonstrate the feasibility of this new mode of transport, which is designed to link different take-off and landing sites known as \\\"vertiports\\\".  There are four vertiports in operation - Paris-Charles-de-Gaulle and Le Bourget airports, the Issy-les-Moulineaux heliport to the south-west of Paris and the Saint-Cyr-l'Ecole airfield near Versailles.  A fifth site, a barge on the Seine at Austerlitz, has yet to receive the go-ahead from the Ministry of Transport, but \\\"it's ready, moored, positioned\\\".  Do not miss:Neglected European resort set to be restored to its former glory in \\u00a3114m plan  Do not miss:New \\u00a3107m road that will improve access to world-famous touri  Do not miss:The \\u00a368m bridge that stretches 666 metres and breathes fire  \\\"It's an aeronautical programme, so we know it's complex,\\\" explained Jean-Christophe Drai, Volocopter's manager for France.  \\\"Sometimes you discover things as you go along. So yes, there has been a bit of a delay. We are still aiming to obtain this certification in the autumn.\\\"  We use your sign-up to provide content in ways you have consented to and to improve our understanding of you. This may include adverts from us and 3rd parties based on our understanding. You can unsubscribe at any time. Read ourPrivacy Policy  Edward Arkwright, executive director of ADP said: \\\"We will not have any paying passengers during the Olympic and Paralympic Games. But our objective remains to have a fare-paying passenger before the end of the year.\\\"  Volocopter began selling 1,000 tickets for VoloCity air taxi rides in Paris in 2020 for \\u00a3255 each with the flight time to be a 15-minute spin.  SEARCH  CONNECT WITH US  TODAY'S PAPER  See today's front and back pages, download the newspaper, order back issues and use the historic Daily Express newspaper archive.  EXPRESS.CO.UK  Daily Express uses notifications to keep you updated\"}"